HEADWORD: Diocese
<hw>Di"o*cese</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Dioceses</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>diocise</ets>,
OF. <ets>diocise</ets>, F. <ets>dioc⟦eacute⟧se</ets>, L.
<ets>dioecesis</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ housekeeping, administration, a
province, a diocese, fr. <?/ to keep house, manage; <grk>dia`</grk>
through + <?/ to manage a household, <?/ a house. See
<er>Economy</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>The circuit or extent
of a bishop's jurisdiction; the district in which a bishop exercises his
ecclesiastical authority.</def> <altsp>[Frequently, but improperly,
spelt <asp>diocess</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

